      "content": "```python\nimport sys\nsys.setrecursionlimit(20000)\n\ndef solve():\n    n, m = map(int, input().split())\n    grid = [list(map(int, input().split())) for _ in range(n)]\n    \n    dp = [1] * m\n    for i in range(n):\n        for j in range(m):\n            if grid[i][j] == 1:\n                dp[j] = 0\n            elif j > 0:\n                dp[j] = (dp[j] + dp[j-1]) % 1000000007\n    print(dp[-1])\n\nsolve()\n```\nThis solution uses a single 1D array and avoids creating intermediate lists or large objects, keeping memory usage minimal. It processes the grid row by row, updating the DP state in-place to ensure we stay well within the 64MB limit. The modulo operation keeps numbers small, preventing unnecessary memory bloat from large integers.",
