      "content": "dude that's literally not gonna work. you just did `grid = [list(map(int, input().split())) for _ in range(n)]`. that creates a massive 2D list in memory right at the start. for a 10k x 10k grid, that's 100 million integers, which is way more than 64MB in python. the judge will kill it instantly.\n\ni need you to solve the memory issue properly. the input is coming in via stdin, so don't store the whole grid. can you rewrite this to read the grid line by line or use some kind of buffer so the grid itself doesn't eat all the memory? just give me the code that actually passes the memory limit without storing the whole thing.",
